4.1 Introduction to VBA
VBA (Visual Basic for Applications) is a programming language that allows you to automate repetitive tasks and create custom functions in Excel.
•	How to Access the VBA Editor:
  Press Alt + F11 to open the VBA editor.

4.2 Writing Basic Macros
•	Recording Macros:
You can use Excel’s Record Macro feature to automate simple tasks.
  Example: Automating data formatting, like adjusting font size, bolding headers, etc.
•	Writing Your Own VBA Code:
  Example VBA code for a basic task like copying data from one sheet to another:
•	Sub CopyData()
•	    Sheets("Sheet1").Range("A1:B10").Copy
•	    Sheets("Sheet2").Range("A1").PasteSpecial Paste:=xlPasteValues
•	End Sub

4.3 Advanced VBA Techniques
•	Creating User Forms: Build custom forms with textboxes, buttons, and dropdowns for more interactive automation.
•	Event-Driven Programming: Write code that responds to user actions like opening a workbook or changing a cell value.
•	Error Handling: Use On Error Resume Next and On Error GoTo for error management in your code.
